CaseSummary.Summary: Vehicle one (V1 - case vehicle), a 1998 Mercury Grand Marquis, 4-door sedan was traveling east in the eastbound lane of a two-lane, two-way rural road. Vehicle two (V2), a 2002 GMC Savanna, cargo van was also traveling east and was ahead of V1. It was daylight, the weather was clear, and the bituminous road surface was dry. The driver of V2 observed that the vehicle in front of him was stopped, waiting for traffic to clear, so as to make a left turn and brought his vehicle to a stop behind this non-contact vehicle. The driver of V1 was reportedly confused while attempting to disengage his cruise control system and could not avoid striking V2. The driver of V1 reportedly attempted to avoid V2 by steering right but the front of V1 struck the rear of V2 in an offset manner. The impact caused V2 to move forward and rotate clockwise slightly before coming to rest in the eastbound lane. The impact casued V1 to also rotate clockwise slightly and V1 came to rest on the right (south) shoulder. Both vehicles were towed due to disabling vehicle damage. The 57-year-old male driver of V2 sustained unknown injuries and was transported to local hospital by ground ambulance. The 80-year-old male driver of V1 (case occupant) was not using the available three-point seat belt but the steering-wheel air bag deployed. He was transported via ground ambulance to a local hospital and later transferred to a regional level-one trauma center.

CirenCaseForm.InjuryAnalysis:
The case occupant is the 163 cm, 80 kg (5 ft 4 in, 176 lb), 80-year-old driver of a 1998 Mercury Grand Marquis, 4-door sedan. The case vehicle struck the rear of a stopped 2002 GMC Savanna, cargo van in an offset manner. The impact was classified as moderate. The WinSMASH reconstruction program (Missing Vehicle Algorithm) calculated a delta-v of 28 kmph (17 mph), which appeared to be borderline but in the general range of values consistent with the observed vehicle damage. The case occupant was alone in the vehicle and was not using the available three-point seat belt. The steering-wheel air bag deployed.
In response to the 12 o'clock direction of impact force, the driver moved forward relative to the vehicle interior. He sustained a contusion to the left parietal scalp and a brief loss of consciousness probably due to contact with the headrest during the rebound phase of this crash. He sustained eight rib fractures (left anterior #5-8 and right anterior #5-8) from contact with the steering-wheel air bag. He sustained two left transverse process fractures to L3 and L5 from torso rotation, which was caused by contact with the air bag and crash forces. He sustained a left intertrochanteric femur fracture, a left central acetabular fracture, and a non-displaced left inferior pubic rami fracture from left knee contact with the knee bolster.
